e impulses that gave rise to it had yet to be fully explored. Curious and Modern Inventions offers fresh insight into the motivating forces behind this music, tracing it to a new conception of instruments of all sorts—whether musical, artistic, or scientific—as vehicles of discovery. Rebecca Cypess shows that early modern thinkers were fascinated with instrumental technologies. The telescope, the clock, the pen, the lute—these were vital instruments for leading thinkers of the age, from Galileo Galilei to Giambattista Marino. No longer used merely to remake an object or repeat a process already known, instruments were increasingly seen as tools for open-ended inquiry that would lead to new knowledge. Engaging with themes from the history of science, literature, and the visual arts, this study reveals the intimate connections between instrumental music and the scientific and artisanal tools that served to mediate between individuals and the world around them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aInstrumental musiczItalyy17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiczItalyy17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  adiscovery, science, innovation, invention, galileo, instrumental music, instruments, telescope, clock, pen, lute, giambattista marino, inquiry, research, literature, visual arts, tools, marini biagio, affetti musicali, carlo farina, frescobaldi girolamo, castello dario, 17th century, history, nonfiction, solo, ensemble, strings, early modern, interdisciplinary, experimental philosophy, material culture, painting, collections, renaissance, classical.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022631944540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226319582423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document